{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"6b9266f98c184673","x":-192,"y":-279,"width":432,"height":559,"type":"file","file":"Uncategorized/Early 2000's internet forums.md"},
		{"id":"e5bdf20487b5e355","x":280,"y":-240,"width":420,"height":580,"type":"file","file":"Uncategorized/Furry art.md"},
		{"id":"e01b47e8557b31a4","x":740,"y":-60,"width":472,"height":440,"type":"text","text":"i get to the beach with a lover. we dance, feel the sand under our feet, revel in beauty and scents and wind. the contemporary idea of art pops into my mind and i wonder if i ought to stop this experience to capture it with a photograph, or pull out my sketchbook, or journal. current ideas about art tell me that this is what art is for, or how art works: it is the self-expression of an individual of their own inspirational experience, that is, of an experience that inspires artistic work. \n\nbut which part of the experience necessitates this? what silliness is this, that asks us to stop the experience at hand to reproduce it in some other form? Unless that experience of reproduction is itself folded back into the experience that thus inspired it, which is possible, but feels arbitrary, art has no place in this experience. There is no natural expression, at least for me, of life that leads to creating an art object depicting it. \n\nPotentially this is a problem that can be solved through that folding back onto itself, but this feels like a solution to an invented problem, the problem of needing inspiration for the creation of artistic work and of the need for the creation of artistic work itself. My own need is unique to me, as someone succumbing to a sunk-cost of an art education and the resulting desire to paint rather than work a traditional job (which itself is partly a result of the awful and pointless experience of work under capitalism), but my particular experience is nested along with every other artist's particular experience within a shared reality of creative work under capitalism. \n\nThe creative economy, as it is now called, has no inherent connection to our culture except as:\n1. an attempt to create new culture out of cloth wholesale, in reaction to a dearth of acceptable culture\n2. an attempt to salve the wounds our society has inflicted upon us\n\nCreative work, the work of artisans and artists, is thus largely relegated to the reproduction of capital and is thus constrained to the goal of capital, that is, ever-increasing capital accumulation, and that goal alone. \n\nWhereas in the past, art was simply the results of humans' natural creative engines being close in time and space to the activities of their culture (imagine inquiring, with disbelief, why plants don't simply attract pollinators in a more efficient way than with gorgeous fields of flowers), in contemporary culture, the work of artists are not only no longer strictly required, but no longer affordable (and not just for the appreciator, but for the creator themselves).\n\n\n\n\n\nthe feeling is that this dance is not enough, the smell of seafoam is not enough, my lover's eyes aren't enough. this moment, this time, must contribute to my income. as artists who are able to see beauty in everything, when everything is available to use as content of creative work, and so much of our waking experience is fear of destitution, and creative work is our main vehicle of income generation, the entire world of our experience is quietly sublated into the idea of money itself. \n\nWhen the activities of life no longer have the necessary conditions to bloom art, art ceases to be an experience intimately tied to life. It becomes something separate and apart from common life. Being then rare, it gains economic value in the market, and the price, keeping the accumulation of art objects to the wealthy and powerful, induces the common person to experiences art as a talisman of high culture. Objects kept away, behind glass, behind ticketed museum lobbies. \n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n"},
		{"id":"51e81a8c60a738e1","x":1260,"y":-60,"width":418,"height":440,"type":"text","text":"p. 9-10\n\n*\"Even a crude experience, if authentically an experience, is more fit to give a clue to the intrinsic nature of esthetic experience than is an object already set apart from any other mode of experience.* \n\n***Following this clue we can discover how the work of art develops and accentuates what is characteristically valuable in things of everyday enjoyment.*** \n\n*The art product will then be seen to issue from the latter, when the full meaning of ordinary experience is expressed, as dyes come out of coal tar products when they receive special treatment.\"*\n\n"},
		{"id":"e99e13782023fc8c","x":1740,"y":-36,"width":388,"height":216,"type":"text","text":"the devaluation of common creative work may simply be a mirror of the larger devaluation of common cultural work in the general sense."},
		{"id":"c486bef65373e1f6","x":1811,"y":223,"width":349,"height":357,"type":"text","text":"how can a community reproduce its culture and find pride in it if it cannot afford the time to create the art that reproduces itself? \n\nThe scaffolding of everyday life, requiring *some* kind of adornment by now as cultural habit, is instead adorned by rote and by outside forces, and cheaply at that, as we fall further and further into poverty. Having no culture to connect with, our energy and passion to reproduce it withers and dies. "},
		{"id":"ba97199305278e5a","x":1118,"y":-507,"width":442,"height":107,"color":"6","type":"text","text":"What can we learn from Dewey that can help us transition back into meaningful culture that demands and grows creativity?"},
		{"id":"1a7d502f922f6b9a","x":2193,"y":219,"width":587,"height":561,"type":"text","text":"p.14-15\n\nlife, and art, is in the jump from one stone to another, and the compelling force is the tension between thought and material reality that necessitates travel from the first stone to the second. meaning is generated through this tension and its attempted resolution, and that meaning is encoded into art objects and creative experiences.\n\nit is thus a necessary condition of creative work that there be belief that change is possible, that tension is resolvable. This does not mean that the change must be made manifest in the physical world, or must even have a greater than zero percent chance of happening; a psychic change can suffice, whether it be Goya coming to terms with the evil he experienced as a court painter in Spain by desperately releasing demons upon the walls of his dining room, hidden until after his death, or by the hobbyist flower painter calming the anxieties of late life through how-to-paint books, filling their home with amateurish canvases. To add greater clarity, one must imagine that elderly hobby painters will become less and less common as the retirement age continues to rise and capital accumulation continue to flow from the poor to the rich. Creative work is labor– labor requires time– and time is becoming more and more expensive.\n\nGiven art's necessary condition of possible change, the reason for our reduced creative output is laid bare: we no longer believe in our hearts that change is possible. p.16 *\"In one wholly perturbed, conditions could not even be struggled with.\"*\n\nDid residents of Auschwitz-Birkenau create art? What kind, and why?\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n"}
	],
	"edges":[]
}